prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: band 6, continuum, 12CO, 13CO, C18O
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: It is majorly for single continuum obervation setup of 138 objects (97 FDs + 41 TDs) with Fnu > 0.85 mJy at band 6 for greater than 4-sigma detection. In addition to the continuum, we also set to detect 12CO, 13CO, and C18O for disk kinematics.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Our primary goal of this proposal is to detect dust continuum emission at band 6. Along the continuum emission, we also want to get 12CO (2-1), 13CO (2-1), and C18O (2-1) lines. Therefore we choose two basebands for continuum (217 GHz and 232 GHz), and 12CO, 13CO, and C18O can be placed nicely in other two basebands. For this setting the LO is at 225.3 GHz. Our choice of the representative baseband is a baseband for the continuum at 217 GHz. Our choice of the representative frequency reduces requested observation time while satisfying S/N greater than 4 for the continuum detection.
The flux density estimation have been made by extrapolating SEDs in IR (upto 300 micron) wavelength range, then we adopt spectral index (alpha = 2.5), which was measured from one of our sources measured with JCMT and SMA, to extrapolate it to 1.3 mm (ALMA band 6). Because we do not aim to resolve the disk and the synthesized beam size is expected to be the dusty disk size (~100AU), the estimated flux density is used for the peak continuum flux density per beam. The flux density of the faintest source in the proposal is 0.85 mJy. We can detect 70% of our sources with S/N > 5.
We also plan to detect bright CO lines if gas density is thick enough. Assuming that the disk propoerties are similar to the disks in Taurus already observed and catalogued, we adopted the average peak flux density of 13CO (2-1) line of Taurus disks (DM Tau, GG Tau, LkCa 15, etc) as a reference value, then we measure the expected peak flux density of our sources considering the distance of Orion. This gives about 300 mJy for the peak flux density of interesting line. The reason to choose 13CO as the reference line to justify the S/N of line emission is because the flux density of 13CO is generally weaker than 12CO and stronger than C18O based on the single dish observations of T Tauri disks.
If there is a reported radial velocity, we entered the reported radial velocity. For the objects without reported radial velocities, we entered the radial velocity of the cloud which is about 10 km/s.

We chose the respresentative spectral window for continuum. That is why the representative spectral window resolution is 43.17 km/s. For the basebands for line of interests (12CO, 13CO, and C18O), we set the spectral resolution is about 0.2 km/s. This gives line width / the spectra resolution of line of interest equals 10 (2 km/s / 0.2 km/s). We set the spectral window widths as 150~160 km/s. We set this wide spectral window for the possibility to cover any outflow or remaining envelope if any of them exist. If thereis no such an additional component confusing the emission from CO molecules in disks, there will be many line-free channels in each baseband, those channels contribute to increase the S/N of continuum emission.

We request the angular resolution of 0.25 arcsec because it corresponds to ~100 AU at the distance of Orion A (d~400 pc). 100 AU of disk size is the disk size adopted by the most disk models for the dust continuum. We do not aim to resolve a disk's radial structure via dust continuum. Our main interest is to get the total flux density of continuum emission, and 0.25" of angular resolution will not only reduce the total observing time but also cover our goal.
There are several references reporting that the gaseous disks extend to several thousand AU scales. The requested largest angular resoltuion is 5 arcsec to recover the gaseous disks extended about two thousand AU. From CO emission lines, we will be able to anlayze the gas density structures of disks.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to take dust continuum survey of 138 Class II YSOs in the Orion A star-forming region. We plan to use band 6 to get continuum emission and 12CO (2-1), 13CO (2-1), and C18O (2-1) emission lines. Our major goals are (1) to measure disk mass from the band 6 contimuum emission and (2) to get disk kinematics of YSOs in Orion A using CO emissions for the first time. The disk masses will be used to test disk evolution and planet formation/evolution mechanisms with other properties we have alread acheived -- stellar mass, mass accretion rates, gap sizes of transitional disks, etc. This observation will be also offer the large catalogue of CO (2-1) emission lines of protoplanetary disks in Orion A. We will combine the proposed observation with JCMT/SCUBA2 survey of YSOs in Orion A to measure spectral slopes of their SEDs, which will help us to test the degree of grain growth of disks in Orion compared to that in Taurus. From the proposed less than 10 hours observation, we can achieve many observables to understand disk evolution and planet formation.
